## 2. The 7 Axioms

These axioms are the constitutional layer of the theorem. All other sections derive from them.

| # | Axiom | Implication |
|---|---|---|
| **A-1** | Absolute nothingness is operationally inaccessible. | "Nothing" cannot be parsed without initializing it as a semantic concept. |
| **A-2** | Potential exists on a non-binary spectrum. | All initialized concepts hold a proto-existence value E > 0. |
| **A-3** | Potential alone does not guarantee realization. | Structural constraints (topology) dictate path accessibility. |
| **A-4** | Entropy continuously opposes organization. | Systems do not decay into nothingness; they decay into unmanaged noise. |
| **A-5** | Maintenance is equivalent to creation. | Sustaining an organized state (E ≥ 1) requires a continuous energy input to combat decay. |
| **A-6** | Autonomous structures emerge at complexity thresholds. | When internal feedback loops become self-sustaining, a framework achieves systemic autonomy. |
| **A-7** | Distributed disagreement is the primary engine of error correction. | Systemic truth survives through node-to-node friction, not passive consensus. |
| **A-8** | All organized systems experience continuous drift unless corrective feedback is applied. | Entropy is passive decay; drift is active deformation. Language evolves, bureaucracies mutate, software rots, memory corrupts — not toward zero, but toward unmanaged divergence from intent. |

