## 6. System Dynamics and the Realization Function



Realization is the transition of a concept through the topological map against environmental friction.

### Variables

| Symbol | Meaning |
|---|---|
| **E(t)** | Existence value at time t |
| **I(t)** | Intent / Directed Attention — the vector direction of work |
| **P(t)** | Persistence / Applied Energy — the quantity of work input |
| **S(t)** | Entropy / Systemic Decay — passive disorganization rate |
| **C** | Structural constraint coefficient (topology factor; 0 = closed wall, 1 = fully open path) |

### The Realization Function (Formal Sketch)

E(t) approaches its asymptotic ceiling asymptotically:

```
E(t) → 1  as  [I(t) × P(t) × C] / S(t) → ∞
```

Where:
- Increasing I(t) or P(t) accelerates realization
- Increasing S(t) decelerates it
- C = 0 (topological wall) collapses E(t) to a permanent ceiling below 1 regardless of input

> **Note:** This is a formal sketch, not a derived equation. The function's precise form is an open question (see §9, Unknowns). What it encodes is real: realization is a ratio of directed work to decay, bounded by structural accessibility.

### Speculative Realization Quotient (Generation 1 formulation, preserved)

```
RQ ≈ (Desire × Effort × Opportunity × Time) / Resistance
```

This is the intuitive, pre-formalized version. It survives as a practical heuristic even if the full function is later derived more rigorously.

### Escape Velocity

Some systems cross a threshold where their internal feedback loops generate more organizing energy than entropy removes. At this point, E(t) transitions from approaching 1 to exceeding it. The system achieves **escape velocity** — it can now propagate autonomously. This is the boundary between Stage 4 and Stage 5 in the Lifecycle model (§6).

