## 10. Cognitive Dynamics, Ethics, and Discipline

Because thoughts establish immediate E > 0 trajectories, cognitive architecture requires active input filtration. Attention is a finite energy resource. What receives attention receives work input P(t).

### Starve at the Gate (Cognitive Firewalls)

Maladaptive or destructive feedback loops are easiest to neutralize at initialization (E → 0+). Because attacking an idea directly allocates processing power to it — increasing its structural weight — loops must be starved via **pointer reallocation**.

> Do not attempt to erase a node. Reallocate the system's processing pointer to a parallel, constructive architecture.

This is not suppression. It is resource starvation combined with architectural substitution.

### Ethical Weight of Thought

Thoughts carry moral significance because they influence trajectories. This is not mysticism — it is a consequence of A-2. A thought at E > 0, fed with attention (P(t)), moves along the realization curve. Early-stage thoughts are cheap to redirect; late-stage realized patterns are expensive to dismantle.

*This was the original ethical insight of Generation 1, and it survives translation into systems language intact.*

### Positive and Negative Loops

| Positive Loops | Negative Loops |
|---|---|
| Compassion, discipline, wisdom, forgiveness | Hatred, deceit, addiction, cycles of revenge |

Both compound. Both can achieve escape velocity. The asymmetry is that negative loops often achieve escape velocity faster due to lower initialization energy (fear and threat response are evolutionarily primed).

### Hurt People Hurt People

Trauma propagates through recursive loops. Cycles persist unless interrupted. Compassion and accountability function as **damping mechanisms** — they inject negative feedback into a positive feedback loop, reducing amplitude over successive iterations.

### Memory and System Maintenance

Discipline is a compounding function. Small, iterative corrections represent continuous low-energy maintenance loops that keep cognitive and operational systems from drifting into entropic noise. The cost of maintaining discipline is always lower than the cost of rebuilding it from collapse.

