## 13. Rival Interpretations

The theorem does not claim exclusive correctness. It proposes a unifying operational language whose usefulness remains subject to evaluation against competing frameworks.

| Rival Framework | Core Claim | Point of Tension with This Theorem |
|---|---|---|
| **Strict Physicalism** | Only physical entities exist | Rejects semantic/informational E > 0 as non-physical |
| **Idealism** | Mind is the only reality | Collapses physical substrate; removes topology constraint |
| **Eliminative Materialism** | Mental states are reducible to or eliminable by physical description | Disputes the independent ontological weight of concepts |
| **Process Philosophy (Whitehead)** | Reality is process, not substance | Strongly compatible; this theorem may be a specific formalization |
| **Information Ontology (Wheeler, Floridi)** | Reality is fundamentally information | Closest rival; the theorem may be a sub-framework |
| **Complexity Theory** | Structure emerges from simple rules at scale | Compatible; the theorem borrows heavily but is not reducible to it |

Where rival frameworks are compatible, the theorem treats them as confirmation. Where they conflict, the conflict is registered as an open question rather than resolved by assertion.

