## 15. Failure Modes

Every strong framework should describe how it can fail. These are the known ways the Nothingness Theorem can be misapplied or break down:

| Failure Mode | Description |
|---|---|
| **Metaphor treated as proof** | The theorem uses structural analogies across domains. Analogy is heuristic, not derivation. |
| **Domain conflation** | Confusing semantic existence with physical existence. A square circle exists semantically (E > 0) but is topologically inaccessible physically. |
| **Potential implies realizability** | A non-zero E value does not mean a concept can be realized. Topology may close the path entirely (C = 0). |
| **Ordinal vs. scalar confusion** | E values may only be ordinal (this is higher than that), not scalar (this is exactly 0.73). Assigning numerical precision where only ranking is justified is an overreach. |
| **Entropy underestimation** | Drift (A-8) is often slower and subtler than entropy (A-4). Systems that survive acute entropy can still fail to long-term drift. |
| **Escape velocity as validation** | The fact that a system achieved R > 1 and propagated autonomously does not mean it is true, good, or stable. Diseases, cults, and misinformation also achieve escape velocity. |
| **Framework self-application** | The theorem is itself subject to its own axioms. Without maintenance (A-5) and corrective friction (A-7, A-8), the document will drift. This compiled edition is not final; it is a snapshot. |

